<section class="guideSection" id="seed-packet-graveyard">
  <h2>The Seed Packet Graveyard</h2>

  <p>
    The worst seed organizer is not always the messiest one. Sometimes it is the neatest box on the shelf: packets sorted, labels facing forward, and planting windows quietly passing while the seeds stay untouched.
  </p>

  <p>
    A perfect container of forgotten seeds is still a failed system. The organizer should help you answer the question that matters during the growing season: what needs to be planted, tested, used first, or replaced next?
  </p>

  <div class="calloutBox">
    <h2>The Organizer Test</h2>

    <p>
      A seed organizer should not only store packets. It should keep old seeds from disappearing, active seeds from being forgotten, and useful varieties from being bought twice.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    This is why the best seed storage organizer is usually not the most elaborate one. It is the system you can maintain before seed-starting season, during direct-sowing windows, and after harvest when saved seeds and leftover packets need to go somewhere useful.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="planting-queue">
  <h2>The Planting Queue Method</h2>

  <p>
    The Planting Queue Method organizes seeds by what needs to happen next. Instead of treating every packet as equal, it separates seeds into action categories: plant soon, use first, direct sow later, test before planting, archive, and buy again.
  </p>

  <p>
    This works because most seed-storage mistakes are timing mistakes. Seeds are started too late, older packets are ignored, fall crops are forgotten, and empty packets stay mixed in with active seed.
  </p>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Seed Status</th>
          <th>What It Means</th>
          <th>Where It Belongs</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Plant soon</strong></td>
          <td>Seeds needed in the next indoor-starting, direct-sowing, or transplant-prep window.</td>
          <td>Front binder section, top photo case, or clearly marked current-season folder.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Use first</strong></td>
          <td>Older packets, partial packets, or seeds with limited quantity.</td>
          <td>A visible use-first section instead of the back of a crop category.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Direct sow later</strong></td>
          <td>Warm-season or succession crops that should not be planted yet.</td>
          <td>Later-season tab, inner photo case, or direct-sow folder.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Fall planting</strong></td>
          <td>Seeds that are easy to forget during spring-focused planning.</td>
          <td>Separate fall garden section.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Test before planting</strong></td>
          <td>Old or uncertain packets that may have weak germination.</td>
          <td>Germination-test section with the packet year visible.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Archive</strong></td>
          <td>Backup packets, saved seeds, or seeds you are not actively browsing this season.</td>
          <td>Airtight box, jar, or sealed container with labels.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Buy again</strong></td>
          <td>Empty packets from varieties you want to grow again.</td>
          <td>Buy-again section, shopping list, or inventory sheet.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    The point is not to build a complicated filing system. The point is to make the next planting decision obvious when the season gets busy.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="active-vs-archive">
  <h2>Active Seeds vs Archive Seeds</h2>

  <p>
    One common mistake is trying to make one organizer do every job. Active seeds need visibility and quick access. Archive seeds need protection. Saved seeds need labels. Empty packets need a shopping-list role instead of staying in the active collection.
  </p>

  <p>
    Separating active seeds from archive seeds makes the whole system easier to maintain.
  </p>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Seed Group</th>
          <th>Best Organizer Style</th>
          <th>Why It Works</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Current-season seeds</strong></td>
          <td>Binder, photo case, or accordion folder</td>
          <td>Easy to browse while planning and planting.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Older seeds to use first</strong></td>
          <td>Clearly marked use-first section</td>
          <td>Prevents old packets from hiding behind newer ones.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Backup packets</strong></td>
          <td>Airtight box or sealed container</td>
          <td>Better protection from humidity swings and rough handling.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Saved seeds</strong></td>
          <td>Labeled envelopes in a sealed box</td>
          <td>Keeps variety, year, and source information attached to the seed.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Empty favorite packets</strong></td>
          <td>Buy-again section or inventory sheet</td>
          <td>Preserves the variety name without making the active organizer misleading.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    For many gardeners, the best setup is not one perfect container. It is an active-season organizer plus a protected archive for seeds that do not need to be handled every week.
  </p>
</section>

